# Connect the DUT ({{ ip }}, phase 1)

## Precondition

Freshly generated environment: `make -C sim compile` already passes using the
DUT stub (`+define+{{ IP }}_USE_DUT_STUB` — the Makefile prints a
"generated DUT stub" note while `dut.rtl_filelist` does not resolve).

## Goal

Instantiate the real `{{ dut.module }}` in `tb/{{ ip }}_tb_top.sv` with every
port connected, replacing the `TODO(connect-dut)` block. uvm-gen does not
parse RTL — the port list comes from the design sources.

## Relevant files

* `tb/{{ ip }}_tb_top.sv` — the `dut` instantiation with TODO(connect-dut)
* `cfg/{{ cfg_relname }}` — `dut.rtl_filelist` points at the RTL filelist
  ({{ dut.rtl_filelist or "NOT SET YET — fill it in first" }}; relative paths
  resolve against the config file's directory)
{% for a in agents %}
* `agents/{{ a.name }}_agent/{{ ip }}_{{ a.name }}_if.sv` — '{{ a.name }}' interface signals (extend them to match the DUT port groups)
{% endfor %}
{% for v in vips %}
* `vip/{{ v.name }}_vip/` — Cadence {{ v.title }} VIP wrapper for '{{ v.name }}': ports that belong to this VIP are that wrapper's TODO(vip) job, not a custom interface here.
{% endfor %}

## Procedure

1. Read the `{{ dut.module }}` module declaration directly from the RTL
   (`dut.rtl_filelist`, following any nested `-f` includes) to get the exact
   port list — do not guess it from the interface stubs or from memory.
2. Match every port to an owner:
   * belongs to an existing custom interface (name/width matches the
     protocol that interface's agent was written for) → extend that
     interface's signal list AND its `drv_cb`/`mon_cb` clocking blocks with
     the real signal, and update the matching driver/monitor in the same
     pass — a port wired into the interface but never read/driven by the
     agent is only half connected;
{% if vips %}
   * belongs to one of the Cadence VIPs above → leave it, the VIP wrapper's
     own TODO(vip) markers own it;
{% endif %}
   * clock/reset-like → `clk`/`rst_n`;
   * matches nothing (test modes, DFT, unused straps) → tie it off directly
     in the instantiation with a one-line comment stating why.
3. If a port's owner genuinely isn't inferable from its name/width against
   the interfaces above, stop and ask rather than guessing a mapping — and
   say so explicitly if a port needs an interface/agent this environment
   doesn't have yet (that's a new-agent job, not a wiring job).
4. Ensure the RTL filelist path in `cfg/{{ cfg_relname }}` resolves; the
   Makefile then compiles the real RTL automatically instead of the stub.

If this environment was generated inside a repository that also carries the
`dv-dut-integrator` agent and `dut-integration` skill (the dvagent DV
Copilot pack), prefer `/connect-dut {{ ip }}` there — same procedure, with an
explicit plan-approval gate before any interface is edited. The steps above
are the fully self-contained equivalent for standalone use of this env.

## Commands

```bash
make -C sim compile
```

## Done when

`make -C sim compile` is clean (exit 0, no elaboration errors) WITHOUT the
"generated DUT stub" note — i.e. against the real RTL — AND every DUT port
is accounted for: connected to an interface/clk/rst_n, or tied off with a
comment. Zero `// TODO(connect-dut)` markers left. Then continue with
`implement-agents.prompt.md`.
